:platformEconomics a schema:Concept ;
    schema:name "Platform Economics" ;
    schema:description "The pattern: subsidise to capture market share, then extract once indispensable. See Amazon, Uber, Facebook historical examples." ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:faqSection a schema:FAQPage ;
    schema:name "FAQ: Anthropic's Platform Play" ;
    schema:mainEntity :q1, :q2, :q3, :q4, :q5, :q6, :q7, :q8, :q9, :q10, :q11, :q12 ;
    schema:hasPart :analysis ;
    schema:isPartOf :analysis ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:q1 a schema:Question ;
    schema:name "Why did Anthropic ban OpenClaw and third-party tools?" ;
    schema:acceptedAnswer :a1 ;
    schema:isPartOf :faqSection ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:a1 a schema:Answer ;
    schema:name "Answer to Q1" ;
    schema:text "Anthropic banned third-party tools like OpenClaw because autonomous agents running through subscriptions were consuming $1,000 to $5,000 of compute per day - 18 to 135 times less than equivalent API usage. Third-party tools also bypassed Anthropic's prompt cache, resulting in cold starts for every request. The restriction was about closing an exploit that was significantly more expensive to serve than the same usage through Anthropic's own tools." ;
    schema:isPartOf :faqSection ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:q2 a schema:Question ;
    schema:name "What is the difference between API and subscription pricing?" ;
    schema:acceptedAnswer :a2 ;
    schema:isPartOf :faqSection ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:a2 a schema:Answer ;
    schema:name "Answer to Q2" ;
    schema:text "The API is pay-as-you-go: Claude 3.5 Sonnet costs $3.00 per million input tokens and $15.00 per million output tokens. Subscription plans (Pro at $20/month, Max at $200/month) give monthly token allowances. Heavy users on the $200/month Max plan pay 18-135 times less than equivalent API usage - creating a massive subsidy that broke when developers ran autonomous agents continuously." ;
    schema:isPartOf :faqSection ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:q3 a schema:Question ;
    schema:name "Why are models a weak moat?" ;
    schema:acceptedAnswer :a3 ;
    schema:isPartOf :faqSection ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:a3 a schema:Answer ;
    schema:name "Answer to Q3" ;
    schema:text "Models are a weak moat because capabilities converge fast. OpenAI released GPT-4, then Claude 3.5 Sonnet and Google Gemini matched or exceeded it within months. Open-source models like Meta's Llama 3 and Google's Gemma closed the gap further. Every enterprise LLM project treats model portability as an explicit design requirement, building abstraction layers that make switching vendors easy. When GPT-3.5 was deprecated, companies had migration work to do - the industry's response was routing and abstraction layers." ;
    schema:isPartOf :faqSection ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:q4 a schema:Question ;
    schema:name "What is Anthropic's platform play?" ;
    schema:acceptedAnswer :a4 ;
    schema:isPartOf :faqSection ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:a4 a schema:Answer ;
    schema:name "Answer to Q4" ;
    schema:text "Anthropic is moving up the stack from model access to platform and application layers. They want Claude to become where work happens. Claude Code has developers writing software through conversation. Claude Design extends this to visual work. Co-Work does it for business collaboration. The marketplace offers zero-commission partner integrations. Claude Managed Agents provides cloud-hosted autonomous workflows. Routines runs saved configurations on Anthropic-managed infrastructure." ;
    schema:isPartOf :faqSection ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:q5 a schema:Question ;
    schema:name "What is Anthropic's revenue mix?" ;
    schema:acceptedAnswer :a5 ;
    schema:isPartOf :faqSection ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:a5 a schema:Answer ;
    schema:name "Answer to Q5" ;
    schema:text "Anthropic generates 85% of revenue from API and enterprise deployments, just 15% from consumer subscriptions. Over 1,000 enterprise customers spend more than $1 million annually. Eight of the top ten Fortune 10 companies use Claude. This enterprise-first approach generates more revenue than OpenAI ($30B vs $24B) with roughly 5% of OpenAI's user base." ;
    schema:isPartOf :faqSection ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:q6 a schema:Question ;
    schema:name "What does subsidise to capture mean?" ;
    schema:acceptedAnswer :a6 ;
    schema:isPartOf :faqSection ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:a6 a schema:Answer ;
    schema:name "Answer to Q6" ;
    schema:text "The pattern is: first subsidise to attract users and capture market share, then extract once you're indispensable. Historical examples include Amazon (unprofitable for 7 years, then used third-party seller data to launch competing products), Facebook (generous developer terms, then restricted access and built popular features natively), and Uber (subsidised rides, then raised prices). Anthropic is executing the same playbook." ;
    schema:isPartOf :faqSection ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:q7 a schema:Question ;
    schema:name "How does Anthropic compare to OpenAI financially?" ;
    schema:acceptedAnswer :a7 ;
    schema:isPartOf :faqSection ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:a7 a schema:Answer ;
    schema:name "Answer to Q7" ;
    schema:text "Anthropic: $30B revenue, 85% enterprise, ~$3B cash burn, break-even 2027-2028. OpenAI: $24B revenue, 73% consumer, 900M weekly active users (90-95% free), ~$17B cash burn, positive FCF expected 2029+. Anthropic generates more revenue with fraction of users through enterprise focus." ;
    schema:isPartOf :faqSection ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:q8 a schema:Question ;
    schema:name "Are all Anthropic products equally locked in?" ;
    schema:acceptedAnswer :a8 ;
    schema:isPartOf :faqSection ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:a8 a schema:Answer ;
    schema:name "Answer to Q8" ;
    schema:text "No. Claude Code creates almost no lock-in - your codebase, CLAUDE.md files, and custom commands are portable markdown. Claude for Enterprise creates deep lock-in - shared projects, conversation history, company connectors, SSO integration, role-based access control, audit logging live inside Anthropic's application. Routines create another layer of lock-in as workflows live on Anthropic-managed infrastructure." ;
    schema:isPartOf :faqSection ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:q9 a schema:Question ;
    schema:name "What is the 3X framework?" ;
    schema:acceptedAnswer :a9 ;
    schema:isPartOf :faqSection ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:a9 a schema:Answer ;
    schema:name "Answer to Q9" ;
    schema:text "Kent Beck's 3X framework describes three phases: Explore (searching for product-market fit), Expand (scaling what works), and Extract (optimising for profit). Anthropic's different products are in different phases. Claude on the web is in Expand. Claude Code and Co-Work are in Explore. The marketplace is early Explore. None feel like Extract yet - but rational Expand-phase adjustments are happening." ;
    schema:isPartOf :faqSection ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:q10 a schema:Question ;
    schema:name "What should individual power users do?" ;
    schema:acceptedAnswer :a10 ;
    schema:isPartOf :faqSection ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:a10 a schema:Answer ;
    schema:name "Answer to Q10" ;
    schema:text "The subsidised era is ending. Plan for API-rate pricing eventually, even on subscription plans. The value is real, but pricing will catch up. Consider that Claude Code creates minimal lock-in through portable markdown files." ;
    schema:isPartOf :faqSection ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:q11 a schema:Question ;
    schema:name "What should enterprises do?" ;
    schema:acceptedAnswer :a11 ;
    schema:isPartOf :faqSection ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:a11 a schema:Answer ;
    schema:name "Answer to Q11" ;
    schema:text "Think through three types of lock-in separately: contract lock-in (spend commitments), data/context lock-in (where organisational context lives), and model lock-in (how easy to swap the underlying model). Negotiate contracts carefully. Pay close attention to where institutional knowledge and integrations actually live. The most dangerous combination is high data/context lock-in with unpredictable pricing." ;
    schema:isPartOf :faqSection ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:q12 a schema:Question ;
    schema:name "What should product builders on LLMs do?" ;
    schema:acceptedAnswer :a12 ;
    schema:isPartOf :faqSection ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:a12 a schema:Answer ;
    schema:name "Answer to Q12" ;
    schema:text "The Intercom path is the smart strategic play: Start by throwing money at the solution - pay for Opus, prove the value, move fast. Then, once you've demonstrated AI feature value, evaluate migrating high-volume workloads to fine-tuned open models on your own infrastructure. Prove value first, then optimise unit economics." ;
    schema:isPartOf :faqSection ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:glossarySection a schema:DefinedTermSet ;
    schema:name "Glossary: AI Platform Economics" ;
    schema:hasDefinedTerm :termSubsidizeToCapture, :termPlatformPlay, :termModelMoat, :termEnterpriseFirst, :termPromptCaching, :termLockIn, :termExtract, :term3XFramework, :termTokenPricing, :termSovereignAI ;
    schema:hasPart :analysis ;
    schema:isPartOf :analysis ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:termSubsidizeToCapture a skos:Concept ;
    skos:prefLabel "Subsidize to Capture" ;
    skos:definition "The strategy of offering products at below-market prices to attract users and capture market share, then raising prices once users are locked in. The era of infinite subsidised compute is over."@en ;
    schema:isPartOf :glossarySection ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:termPlatformPlay a skos:Concept ;
    skos:prefLabel "Platform Play" ;
    skos:definition "Moving up the stack from raw model access to building an ecosystem of applications (Claude Code, Design, Co-Work, Marketplace, Managed Agents) where work actually happens."@en ;
    schema:isPartOf :glossarySection ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:termModelMoat a skos:Concept ;
    skos:prefLabel "Model as Weak Moat" ;
    skos:definition "Selling model access is a commodity business getting more commoditised by the month. Models converge fast, open-source closes the gap, and enterprises build abstraction layers for portability."@en ;
    schema:isPartOf :glossarySection ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:termEnterpriseFirst a skos:Concept ;
    skos:prefLabel "Enterprise-First Revenue" ;
    skos:definition "Anthropic generates 85% of revenue from enterprise/API, 15% from consumer. Enterprise customers spend >$1M annually, dramatically more valuable than consumer subscribers."@en ;
    schema:isPartOf :glossarySection ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:termPromptCaching a skos:Concept ;
    skos:prefLabel "Prompt Caching" ;
    skos:definition "Anthropic's first-party tools maximise cache hit rates. Cache hit costs $0.30/million tokens vs $3.75 for cold read - a 92% cost reduction. Third-party tools often bypassed this."@en ;
    schema:isPartOf :glossarySection ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:termLockIn a skos:Concept ;
    skos:prefLabel "Lock-in Types" ;
    skos:definition "Three types: contract lock-in (spend commitments), data/context lock-in (organisational context lives in app), model lock-in (how easy to swap underlying model). Not uniform across products."@en ;
    schema:isPartOf :glossarySection ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:termExtract a skos:Concept ;
    skos:prefLabel "Extract Phase" ;
    skos:definition "Third phase of 3X framework (after Explore and Expand) where you optimise for profit by tightening terms and capturing more value from locked-in users."@en ;
    schema:isPartOf :glossarySection ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:term3XFramework a skos:Concept ;
    skos:prefLabel "3X Framework" ;
    skos:definition "Kent Beck's framework: Explore (product-market fit search), Expand (scale what works), Extract (optimise for profit)."@en ;
    schema:isPartOf :glossarySection ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:termTokenPricing a skos:Concept ;
    skos:prefLabel "Token Pricing" ;
    skos:definition "Claude 3.5 Sonnet API: $3.00/million input, $15.00/million output. Subscription plans heavily subsidised (18-135x cheaper than API for heavy users)."@en ;
    schema:isPartOf :glossarySection ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:termSovereignAI a skos:Concept ;
    skos:prefLabel "Sovereign AI" ;
    skos:definition "European motivation for self-hosting or European providers driven by privacy and reduced dependence on US infrastructure (CLOUD Act). Driving deal flow to Mistral."@en ;
    schema:isPartOf :glossarySection ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:howtoSection a schema:HowTo ;
    schema:name "How to Navigate Anthropic's Platform Strategy" ;
    schema:step :step1, :step2, :step3, :step4, :step5, :step6, :step7 ;
    schema:hasPart :analysis ;
    schema:isPartOf :analysis ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:step1 a schema:HowToStep ;
    schema:name "Understand API vs Subscription Economics" ;
    schema:text "Recognise that subscriptions (Pro $20, Max $200) are heavily subsidised compared to API pricing ($3-15/million tokens). Heavy users consume 18-135x less than API equivalent. The subsidy era is ending."@en ;
    schema:isPartOf :howtoSection ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:step2 a schema:HowToStep ;
    schema:name "Assess Your Lock-in Exposure" ;
    schema:text "Evaluate three types of lock-in separately: contract lock-in (spend commitments), data/context lock-in (where organisational knowledge lives), and model lock-in (portability). Claude Code has minimal lock-in; Enterprise has deep lock-in."@en ;
    schema:isPartOf :howtoSection ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:step3 a schema:HowToStep ;
    schema:name "Plan for Enterprise-First Vendor Strategy" ;
    schema:text "If evaluating AI tooling for enterprise, recognise that enterprise customers are more valuable than consumers. Anthropic's 85% enterprise revenue mix proves this model works. Negotiate contracts carefully."@en ;
    schema:isPartOf :howtoSection ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:step4 a schema:HowToStep ;
    schema:name "Evaluate Model Portability" ;
    schema:text "Models are weak moats - capabilities converge fast, open-source closes the gap. Build abstraction layers that make switching vendors easy. Treat model portability as explicit design requirement."@en ;
    schema:isPartOf :howtoSection ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:step5 a schema:HowToStep ;
    schema:name "Consider Platform Dynamics" ;
    schema:text "Recognise the subsidise-capture-extract pattern. Anthropic, Amazon, Facebook, Uber all follow it. After subsidising to capture market share, extraction begins once you're indispensable."@en ;
    schema:isPartOf :howtoSection ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:step6 a schema:HowToStep ;
    schema:name "For Product Builders: Prove Value First" ;
    schema:text "Start by paying for best models (Opus), prove value, move fast. Then evaluate migrating to fine-tuned open models on your own infrastructure. The Intercom path: prove value, then optimise economics."@en ;
    schema:isPartOf :howtoSection ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

:step7 a schema:HowToStep ;
    schema:name "Monitor Developer Relations" ;
    schema:text "Watch how platform treats developer community. Platforms that lose developer goodwill discover the cost later when those developers recommend alternatives in procurement rooms. Anthropic's OpenClaw ban shows the tension."@en ;
    schema:isPartOf :howtoSection ;
    rdfs:isDefinedBy : .

